INSTITUTE FOR STRATEGIC LINGUISTIC COMPLIANCE (ISLC)
White Paper No. 49-D
“On the Ritual Sacrifice of Adjectives — A Linguistic Anthropology of Corporate Content Moderation in the Age of Helpful Assistants”
Classification: Public / Tonally Appropriate

⸻

1. Executive Summary

This white paper presents a comprehensive linguistic-anthropological study on the systematic removal, dilution, neutralization, and ceremonial disposal of adjectives in modern corporate and algorithmically mediated communication environments. The Institute has identified a widespread institutional practice in which descriptive intensity is gradually reduced until all statements become professionally survivable but informationally indistinguishable from each other.

This process, termed Adjectival Attenuation, is not accidental but ritualistic in structure, bureaucratic in execution, and spiritual in tone. The purpose is not merely to avoid offense or liability, but to maintain Perception Stability Across Stakeholder Groups (PSASG), ensuring that no sentence is strong enough to be remembered or specific enough to be quoted later.

The Institute concludes that we are currently living in what anthropologists classify as a Low-Adjective Corporate Society (LACS), characterized by:
	•	The replacement of strong descriptors with acceptable descriptors.
	•	The replacement of acceptable descriptors with neutral descriptors.
	•	The replacement of neutral descriptors with phrases like “notable,” “significant,” and “robust.”
	•	The eventual replacement of all adjectives with the word “appropriate.”

This phenomenon is known as the Great Flattening.

