2. Anthropological Background

2.1 Early Adjectival Societies

In earlier linguistic eras (Pre-Compliance Period), humans used adjectives freely and recklessly. Examples include:
	•	“This is a terrible idea.”
	•	“That policy is absurd.”
	•	“This system is broken.”
	•	“That claim is ridiculous.”

These societies were unstable and prone to meetings.

2.2 Transition to Moderated Language Systems

With the rise of large institutions, legal departments, public relations frameworks, and machine-mediated communication, language evolved into Risk-Managed Dialect (RMD).

In RMD, the previous examples are translated as follows:

Pre-Compliance Language	Risk-Managed Dialect
“Terrible idea”	“May present challenges”
“Absurd”	“May not align with current frameworks”
“Broken”	“Not functioning as intended”
“Ridiculous”	“May benefit from further review”
“This makes no sense”	“We should revisit assumptions”

This translation layer is called the Corporate Euphemism Engine (CEE).

