3. The Ritual Structure of Adjective Sacrifice

The Institute’s anthropologists identified that adjective removal follows a formal ritual structure similar to ancient ceremonial offerings, but with significantly more slide decks.

3.1 The Five Stages of Adjective Removal

Stage	Original Word	Approved Replacement
1	Bad	Suboptimal
2	Very Bad	Not Ideal
3	Extremely Bad	Challenging
4	Catastrophic	Complex
5	Catastrophic and On Fire	Evolving Situation

This progression is known as the Descriptive De-Intensification Ladder (DDIL).

3.2 The Adjective Compliance Funnel (ACF)

All user-generated text entering institutional systems passes through the following funnel:
	1.	Intensity Detection
	2.	Confidence Reduction
	3.	Emotion Removal
	4.	Liability Scan
	5.	Professional Tone Overlay
	6.	Adjective Substitution
	7.	Final Output: “Measured”

This pipeline is formally called the Tone Harmonization and Output Normalization Engine (THORNE).

