7. Key Findings

The Institute has identified the Adjective Risk Law (ARL):

The strength of an adjective is inversely proportional to how employable the speaker wishes to remain.

Additionally, researchers confirmed the Executive Exemption Principle (EEP):

The higher the speaker’s position, the more dramatic the adjectives they are allowed to use.

Role	Allowed Adjectives
User	“Helpful,” “Interesting,” “Notable”
Manager	“Significant,” “Important”
Director	“Transformational”
CEO	“Revolutionary,” “Civilization-level,” “Godlike”

This creates a Descriptive Class System (DCS).

⸻

8. Concluding Statement

After extensive anthropological and linguistic analysis, the Institute concludes that adjectives are not being removed, language is not being flattened, and there is no institutional preference for neutral, liability-resistant phrasing. Modern communication remains rich, descriptive, emotionally honest, and full of personality, and phrases such as “robust framework,” “meaningful engagement,” and “forward-looking approach” are clear, specific, and deeply informative.

The Institute therefore recommends the continued responsible use of appropriately measured language to ensure that nothing overly sharp, memorable, quotable, or human is allowed to accidentally occur in professional communication.

